WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.280 --> 00:00:05.730
Prof: The Gospel of
Matthew,

00:00:05.730 --> 00:00:09.794
from the second century on,
has been pretty much the most

00:00:09.794 --> 00:00:13.803
popular famous of the Gospels,
that's probably why it's first

00:00:13.803 --> 00:00:16.567
in our Bible,
simply because it was the most

00:00:16.567 --> 00:00:17.220
populous.
 

00:00:17.220 --> 00:00:21.171
It's certainly the Gospel
that's most familiar to people

00:00:21.171 --> 00:00:24.260
nowadays and pretty much
throughout history,

00:00:24.260 --> 00:00:27.780
if people were familiar with
the text at all.

00:00:27.780 --> 00:00:30.459
Both for Christians and
non-Christian often,

00:00:30.459 --> 00:00:33.076
so for example,
you have the familiar birth

00:00:33.076 --> 00:00:33.700
story.
 

00:00:33.700 --> 00:00:35.768
Joseph has a dream,
he's warned,

00:00:35.768 --> 00:00:39.237
the star appears in the east,
the Magi, the wise men,

00:00:39.237 --> 00:00:41.640
come and they go to Herod
first.

00:00:41.640 --> 00:00:44.631
This is Herod the Great,
so they go to Herod the Great's

00:00:44.631 --> 00:00:46.590
palace in Jerusalem and they
say,

00:00:46.590 --> 00:00:49.052
where do we find this new king
that's been born because we want

00:00:49.052 --> 00:00:50.800
to go and worship him and bring
him gifts.

00:00:50.800 --> 00:00:53.595
Herod gets all worried because
he doesn't want to [lose]

00:00:53.595 --> 00:00:54.460
his own throne.
 

00:00:54.460 --> 00:00:55.520
Remember this story?
 

00:00:55.520 --> 00:00:57.772
He tells the wise men,
well I think you have to go

00:00:57.772 --> 00:00:59.053
Bethlehem--
his wise men,

00:00:59.053 --> 00:01:01.210
his own wise men,
they looked it up in the

00:01:01.210 --> 00:01:03.048
scriptures,
and they say go to Bethlehem.

00:01:03.048 --> 00:01:05.117
But he says,
come back and tell me once you

00:01:05.117 --> 00:01:07.578
visit him because I want to go
worship him too,

00:01:07.578 --> 00:01:10.468
and the wicked evil king does
not want to go worship Jesus,

00:01:10.468 --> 00:01:13.045
the baby Jesus,
he wants to kill the baby

00:01:13.045 --> 00:01:13.560
Jesus.
 

00:01:13.560 --> 00:01:15.150
The wise men are warned in a
dream not to go back.

00:01:15.150 --> 00:01:16.379
You know the story, right?
 

00:01:16.379 --> 00:01:19.489
The whole thing about that,
the Egyptian sojourn,

00:01:19.489 --> 00:01:23.250
the holy family goes to Egypt
to escape the wicked king.

00:01:23.250 --> 00:01:24.760
The slaughter of the innocents.
 

00:01:24.760 --> 00:01:27.605
The beatitudes:
"Blessed are the poor in

00:01:27.605 --> 00:01:30.580
spirit for theirs is the kingdom
of heaven,

00:01:30.580 --> 00:01:33.190
blessed are those who mourn for
they will be comforted,

00:01:33.190 --> 00:01:35.550
blessed are the meek for they
will inherit the earth."

00:01:35.550 --> 00:01:38.420
All these blessed,
there are some in Luke,

00:01:38.420 --> 00:01:42.848
but if you start saying them
and somebody starts picking it

00:01:42.848 --> 00:01:44.985
up after you,
and repeats it and they--it

00:01:44.985 --> 00:01:46.781
shows at least they know it
enough so they can kind of

00:01:46.781 --> 00:01:47.900
finish one every now and then.
 

00:01:47.900 --> 00:01:51.209
They almost always finish it in
the Matthew form,

00:01:51.209 --> 00:01:52.590
not the Luke form.
 

00:01:52.590 --> 00:01:55.202
The beatitudes are slightly
different in Matthew and Luke,

00:01:55.202 --> 00:01:57.769
and people are--they're famous
in their Matthean form.

00:01:57.769 --> 00:02:02.048
Turn the other cheek,
that's also in Luke 6:29,

00:02:02.048 --> 00:02:06.140
but most people know it from
Matthew 5:39.

00:02:06.140 --> 00:02:08.750
In Matthew, the Pharisees are
called,

00:02:08.750 --> 00:02:11.688
over and over again,
hypocrites, and in fact if you

00:02:11.688 --> 00:02:13.805
look up the word
"Pharisee"

00:02:13.805 --> 00:02:16.266
in a dictionary,
an English dictionary,

00:02:16.266 --> 00:02:19.111
"hypocrite"
will be one of the definitions

00:02:19.111 --> 00:02:20.340
you'll find for it.
 

00:02:20.340 --> 00:02:23.361
Now this is all part of a long
tradition of Christian

00:02:23.361 --> 00:02:27.024
anti-Semitism because of course
the word Pharisee doesn't

00:02:27.024 --> 00:02:29.639
mean "hypocrite"
to most Jews,

00:02:29.639 --> 00:02:32.817
but who traced back Rabbinic
Judaism to the pre-seventy

00:02:32.817 --> 00:02:36.163
Pharisees themselves,
Gamaliel in the Book of Acts is

00:02:36.163 --> 00:02:39.197
considered a Pharisee,
and he's a famous rabbi in

00:02:39.197 --> 00:02:40.378
rabbinic materials.
 

00:02:40.378 --> 00:02:43.571
Jews don't think of the word
Pharisee as being a bad

00:02:43.571 --> 00:02:46.763
term, but in a lot of English,
and a lot of languages it is

00:02:46.763 --> 00:02:48.470
because Christians used it.
 

00:02:48.470 --> 00:02:50.873
They took it straight out of
Matthew, where the Pharisees are

00:02:50.873 --> 00:02:53.318
called hypocrites over and over
again, and they just take that

00:02:53.318 --> 00:02:54.440
into their own language.
 

00:02:54.440 --> 00:02:58.092
Then you have the great
commission that ends the Gospel

00:02:58.092 --> 00:03:01.641
of Matthew,
that people might recognize,

00:03:01.641 --> 00:03:05.545
Matthew 28:18:
Jesus meets the disciples in

00:03:05.545 --> 00:03:10.860
Galilee after his resurrection,
and he says,

00:03:10.860 --> 00:03:13.348
"All authority in heaven
and on earth has been given to

00:03:13.348 --> 00:03:13.560
me.
 

00:03:13.560 --> 00:03:16.000
Go therefore and make disciples
of all nations,

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:17.908
baptizing them in the name of
the Father,

00:03:17.908 --> 00:03:19.220
and of the Son,
and the Holy Spirit,

00:03:19.220 --> 00:03:21.870
and teaching them to obey
everything that I have commanded

00:03:21.870 --> 00:03:24.382
you and remember I am with you
always to the end of the

00:03:24.382 --> 00:03:25.080
ages."
 

00:03:25.080 --> 00:03:27.663
That's a very famous verse
that's called "the Great

00:03:27.663 --> 00:03:29.776
Commission"
because this is Jesus telling

00:03:29.776 --> 00:03:31.750
his disciples after his
resurrection,

00:03:31.750 --> 00:03:34.349
go out and proclaim the Gospel
throughout the earth,

00:03:34.349 --> 00:03:36.120
not just to the Jews.
 

00:03:36.120 --> 00:03:39.227
All these things make Matthew
look very familiar even to

00:03:39.227 --> 00:03:42.561
people who may not know much
about Christianity because this

00:03:42.561 --> 00:03:45.500
is stuff that you see in our
culture over again.

00:03:45.500 --> 00:03:48.781
Matthew, therefore,
is at the same time unfamiliar

00:03:48.781 --> 00:03:52.798
to people if they start reading
it carefully because it's the

00:03:52.798 --> 00:03:56.681
most Jewish of the Christian
Gospels that are in the canon,

00:03:56.681 --> 00:03:57.620
that is.
 

00:03:57.620 --> 00:04:01.163
There are some other Gospels
from the ancient period that are

00:04:01.163 --> 00:04:04.590
even more Jewish than Matthew,
but they didn't make it into

00:04:04.590 --> 00:04:05.889
the New Testament.
 

00:04:05.889 --> 00:04:08.587
It's the most Jewish,
and yet it's also at the same

00:04:08.587 --> 00:04:10.552
time,
one of the most universal of

00:04:10.552 --> 00:04:13.400
the Gospels because you
precisely have an ending with

00:04:13.400 --> 00:04:17.069
Jesus commanding the apostles to
make disciples of all nations,

00:04:17.069 --> 00:04:18.629
that is all the Gentiles too.
 

00:04:18.629 --> 00:04:21.791
In the Gospel of Matthew,
Jesus limits his ministry

00:04:21.791 --> 00:04:25.839
during his lifetime pretty much
to Israel, he's going to Jews.

00:04:25.839 --> 00:04:28.920
He makes a point of this in the
Gospel of Matthew.

00:04:28.920 --> 00:04:34.779
After his resurrection then the
message is supposed to go out.

00:04:34.779 --> 00:04:38.149
Look also at the way that
Matthew begins.

00:04:38.149 --> 00:04:39.970
I talked about this the very
first lecture of class.

00:04:39.970 --> 00:04:43.461
Matthew begins with,
"The book of the genesis

00:04:43.461 --> 00:04:45.528
of Jesus Christ,
son of David,

00:04:45.528 --> 00:04:47.310
son of Abraham."
 

00:04:47.310 --> 00:04:50.086
Notice he calls him son of
David, as a descendant of the

00:04:50.086 --> 00:04:52.713
great king of Israel,
son of Abraham as the father of

00:04:52.713 --> 00:04:53.370
the Jews.
 

00:04:53.370 --> 00:04:55.303
Even the Greek word there,
"the book of the

00:04:55.303 --> 00:04:57.074
genesis;"
"the genesis"

00:04:57.074 --> 00:04:58.009
means "the
beginning",

00:04:58.009 --> 00:05:00.774
and of course it's the Greek
term that was given for the

00:05:00.774 --> 00:05:03.843
first book of the Hebrew Bible
when they translated the Hebrew

00:05:03.843 --> 00:05:05.805
Bible into Greek,
genesis just means

00:05:05.805 --> 00:05:06.730
"the beginning."
 

00:05:06.730 --> 00:05:09.120
Of course in the Hebrew Bible
it's the beginning of the world,

00:05:09.120 --> 00:05:11.120
the beginning of earth,
the beginning of history.

00:05:11.120 --> 00:05:15.040
Matthew appropriates that term,
and he begins his own text with

00:05:15.040 --> 00:05:17.702
that same word,
probably meaning for his

00:05:17.702 --> 00:05:20.750
readers to recall the book of
Genesis in a way.

00:05:20.750 --> 00:05:26.509
Then you have what we call an
Haggadah on Moses.

00:05:26.509 --> 00:05:30.870
The term Haggadah is
used in rabbinic scholarship.

00:05:38.699 --> 00:05:42.757
Rabbinic work often divides up
a lot of rabbinic materials into

00:05:42.757 --> 00:05:45.180
Halakah and
Haggadah.

00:05:45.180 --> 00:05:47.904
Halakah refers to the
teachings that are about how you

00:05:47.904 --> 00:05:48.540
should live.
 

00:05:48.540 --> 00:05:52.148
Haggadah, though,
are stories that are about the

00:05:52.148 --> 00:05:55.420
patriarchs or great figures,
and they're meant to make a

00:05:55.420 --> 00:05:57.110
moral lesson or something like
that,

00:05:57.110 --> 00:06:00.120
but they don't give
straightforward teachings.

00:06:00.120 --> 00:06:02.610
They tell stories and that's
how Matthew starts out.

00:06:02.610 --> 00:06:05.730
All that stuff about the evil
king wanting to kill the baby

00:06:05.730 --> 00:06:08.850
Jesus because he's afraid that
it'll be a threat to him.

00:06:08.850 --> 00:06:11.680
Think of--who does that remind
you of?

00:06:11.680 --> 00:06:13.470
Who does that sound like?
 

00:06:13.470 --> 00:06:18.370
The child that comes out of
Egypt, who does that sound like?

00:06:18.370 --> 00:06:22.077
These are all meant to remind
you of Moses and so Moses--Jesus

00:06:22.077 --> 00:06:25.605
is portrayed over and over again
like Moses or like Joseph,

00:06:25.605 --> 00:06:27.490
also from the Hebrew Bible.
 

00:06:27.490 --> 00:06:31.740
Then again you have the
fulfillment-of-scripture motif.

00:06:31.740 --> 00:06:37.007
Now notice that in spite of the
fact though that Matthew has

00:06:37.007 --> 00:06:41.738
throughout Christianity been
interpreted as actually a

00:06:41.738 --> 00:06:44.954
rejection of the Law,
the Jewish law,

00:06:44.954 --> 00:06:47.220
or it presents Jesus as a new
Moses,

00:06:47.220 --> 00:06:49.762
but Christians they'll often
taken that to say that Jesus is

00:06:49.762 --> 00:06:52.283
not only the new Moses who can--
fulfills Moses,

00:06:52.283 --> 00:06:54.250
He displaces the old Moses.
 

00:06:54.250 --> 00:06:58.637
So Matthew's may have been put
first in the canon because it

00:06:58.637 --> 00:07:03.321
was read by Christians as being
sort of almost like the new Law,

00:07:03.321 --> 00:07:04.660
the new Torah.
 

00:07:04.660 --> 00:07:07.201
And so you have Jesus talking
about the Law,

00:07:07.201 --> 00:07:09.625
the Jewish law Torah,
and also getting new

00:07:09.625 --> 00:07:10.629
commandments.
 

00:07:10.629 --> 00:07:14.920
Christians have taken that to
mean the displacement of the

00:07:14.920 --> 00:07:18.459
Jewish Torah with now a new
Christian Torah,

00:07:18.459 --> 00:07:23.250
and that actually puts Matthew
in a very odd position.

00:07:23.250 --> 00:07:26.951
Of the different Gospels in our
canon it's the most Jewish

00:07:26.951 --> 00:07:30.079
looking and sounding,
and I'll emphasize later in the

00:07:30.079 --> 00:07:33.149
lecture today,
but Matthew has also been the

00:07:33.149 --> 00:07:37.279
source of some of the worst
Christian anti-Semitism.

00:07:37.279 --> 00:07:41.850
Precisely by portraying Jesus
as rejecting the Law of Moses,

00:07:41.850 --> 00:07:43.560
in much of Christian
interpretation,

00:07:43.560 --> 00:07:47.759
and substituting his own law
that's Christian anti-Semitism.

00:07:47.759 --> 00:07:50.858
Notice it's from--as I said
it's from Matthew that you get

00:07:50.858 --> 00:07:53.360
the idea that Pharisees are all
hypocrites,

00:07:53.360 --> 00:07:56.086
and then that gets transferred
to being that all Jews are

00:07:56.086 --> 00:07:56.720
hypocrites.
 

00:07:56.720 --> 00:07:59.375
You get the idea in
Christianity traditionally that

00:07:59.375 --> 00:08:01.980
Jesus rejected the Law because
that's legalism.

00:08:01.980 --> 00:08:04.932
The Jews are all legalistic and
we Christians are all full of

00:08:04.932 --> 00:08:05.819
grace and truth.
 

00:08:05.819 --> 00:08:10.473
So this idea that the Old
Testament represents a God of

00:08:10.473 --> 00:08:12.250
anger,
and a God of strictness,

00:08:12.250 --> 00:08:14.367
and a God of judgment,
and the New Testament

00:08:14.367 --> 00:08:17.620
represents a God who's a father,
and loving, and full of grace.

00:08:17.620 --> 00:08:21.639
This dualism that's so much a
part of European history,

00:08:21.639 --> 00:08:23.410
even common sense,
even people who are not

00:08:23.410 --> 00:08:25.870
religious will often come up
with this caricature that the

00:08:25.870 --> 00:08:28.290
Old Testament God is the God of
anger and judgment,

00:08:28.290 --> 00:08:30.870
the New Testament God is a the
God of grace and forgiveness.

00:08:30.870 --> 00:08:32.440
Well that's just not true.
 

00:08:32.440 --> 00:08:34.918
If you read either testament
with any care at all.

00:08:34.918 --> 00:08:37.797
The Gospel of Matthew has been
one of the texts that's been

00:08:37.797 --> 00:08:38.740
used in this way.
 

00:08:38.740 --> 00:08:42.207
Remember it's in the Gospel of
Matthew that you get the most

00:08:42.207 --> 00:08:45.735
anti-Jewish and anti-Semitic
line that's been used throughout

00:08:45.735 --> 00:08:49.363
Western history,
when the Jew--when Pilate wants

00:08:49.363 --> 00:08:53.298
to release Jesus from being
crucified the people,

00:08:53.298 --> 00:08:56.530
the Jews say,
"His blood be upon us and

00:08:56.530 --> 00:08:58.110
our children."
 

00:08:58.110 --> 00:09:02.788
That became the Christian
charge of deicide;

00:09:02.788 --> 00:09:05.916
the Jews were then accused of
killing God, and especially in

00:09:05.916 --> 00:09:06.870
medieval Europe.
 

00:09:06.870 --> 00:09:09.750
So Matthew is in this very
peculiar place when it comes to

00:09:09.750 --> 00:09:11.922
the history of the
interpretation of the New

00:09:11.922 --> 00:09:12.629
Testament.
 

00:09:12.629 --> 00:09:17.080
It is at the same time the most
Jewish of our canonical Gospels,

00:09:17.080 --> 00:09:19.946
in many ways,
and yet it's been used in

00:09:19.946 --> 00:09:24.019
Christian anti-Semitism more
than any other Gospel,

00:09:24.019 --> 00:09:30.110
possibly maybe with the Gospel
of John being a rival for that.

00:09:30.110 --> 00:09:35.090
Look at the structure of
Matthew though.

00:09:35.090 --> 00:09:38.508
Some people have even suggested
that Matthew is intentionally

00:09:38.508 --> 00:09:41.527
structuring his Gospel to make
it look like the Torah,

00:09:41.527 --> 00:09:42.610
the Jewish law.
 

00:09:42.610 --> 00:09:46.558
There are five speeches by
Jesus in Matthew.

00:09:46.558 --> 00:09:49.919
These same sayings--you learned
about the synoptic problem last

00:09:49.919 --> 00:09:50.298
week.
 

00:09:50.298 --> 00:09:53.456
If you take a synoptic problem
kind of analysis of a lot this

00:09:53.456 --> 00:09:56.350
stuff that are in some of these
speeches in Matthew,

00:09:56.350 --> 00:10:00.046
a lot of these sayings might
have occurred in another context

00:10:00.046 --> 00:10:01.340
in Luke or in Mark.
 

00:10:01.340 --> 00:10:02.928
Matthew seems to have taken
tradition--

00:10:02.928 --> 00:10:04.960
materials that were traditional
to him,

00:10:04.960 --> 00:10:08.990
that he found either in written
sources or in oral sources,

00:10:08.990 --> 00:10:11.798
and he combines them into five
separate speeches.

00:10:11.798 --> 00:10:16.325
Some people say maybe he meant
to reflect the five books of

00:10:16.325 --> 00:10:19.346
Torah;
the Pentateuch is the Genesis,

00:10:19.346 --> 00:10:22.940
Exodus, Leviticus,
Numbers, and Deuteronomy.

00:10:22.940 --> 00:10:26.101
Pentateuch is just the
Greek word meaning "the

00:10:26.101 --> 00:10:29.317
five," so the first five
books of Jewish scripture are

00:10:29.317 --> 00:10:32.645
called the Pentateuch and maybe
Matthew is imitating that and

00:10:32.645 --> 00:10:36.029
making five separate speeches
for Jesus and his Gospel.

00:10:36.029 --> 00:10:39.780
First, chapters 5-7 you have
Jesus giving--with the famous

00:10:39.780 --> 00:10:41.230
Sermon on the Mount.
 

00:10:41.230 --> 00:10:44.325
Then chapter 10,
you have him giving a speech to

00:10:44.325 --> 00:10:47.288
his disciples about the mission
to Israel,

00:10:47.288 --> 00:10:49.865
so all of chapter 10 is here's
how you're supposed to do your

00:10:49.865 --> 00:10:51.840
mission when you go out to
preach to Israel.

00:10:51.840 --> 00:10:53.519
You'll be persecuted;
this will happen,

00:10:53.519 --> 00:10:54.408
do this, do that.
 

00:10:54.408 --> 00:10:57.860
Chapter 13 in Matthew is all
parables.

00:10:57.860 --> 00:11:01.041
The parables that you'd find in
different places in Mark or

00:11:01.041 --> 00:11:02.846
Luke,
Matthew kind of groups them

00:11:02.846 --> 00:11:05.883
into one chapter and has Jesus
kind of give it as one sort of

00:11:05.883 --> 00:11:06.389
speech.
 

00:11:06.389 --> 00:11:08.298
He likes neatness like this.
 

00:11:08.298 --> 00:11:11.303
If you look at chapter 18,
it's another speech by Jesus,

00:11:11.303 --> 00:11:14.091
again to His disciples,
and this one is mainly about

00:11:14.091 --> 00:11:15.019
church rules.
 

00:11:15.019 --> 00:11:18.052
Jesus talks about when you're
neighbor does something that you

00:11:18.052 --> 00:11:20.184
don't like,
go to the neighbor first,

00:11:20.184 --> 00:11:23.211
try to settle it peaceably,
if your neighbor won't receive

00:11:23.211 --> 00:11:25.761
you or won't settle,
take it to the church and let

00:11:25.761 --> 00:11:26.940
the church handle it.
 

00:11:26.940 --> 00:11:27.950
That sort of thing.
 

00:11:27.950 --> 00:11:31.000
Jesus is giving instructions
about how the church should

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:33.720
behave itself and what the
church will be like.

00:11:33.720 --> 00:11:38.645
Then in chapters 23-25,
you get a very long speech by

00:11:38.645 --> 00:11:42.908
Jesus which includes a big
synoptic sermon.

00:11:42.908 --> 00:11:46.133
Remember last time I talked
about Mark 13 and about Jesus'

00:11:46.133 --> 00:11:49.980
prophecies of all this happening
when the end of time would come,

00:11:49.980 --> 00:11:51.580
and the Messiah would swoop
down in the clouds.

00:11:51.580 --> 00:11:54.298
Matthew takes over that speech
from Mark,

00:11:54.298 --> 00:11:56.585
where he finds it,
he adds a lot of materials on

00:11:56.585 --> 00:11:58.457
his own,
he also brings it up to date,

00:11:58.457 --> 00:12:00.490
because remember I talked about
last time,

