00:14:35.158 --> 00:14:37.749
One of the things that I'm
trying to teach you in my

00:14:37.749 --> 00:14:41.000
lectures is: what does it mean
to do an exegesis of this text?

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:43.552
Because you're going to have to
write exegesis of your own and

00:14:43.552 --> 00:14:45.977
this Friday your section leads
will walk you through how to

00:14:45.977 --> 00:14:47.149
write an exegesis paper.
 

00:14:47.149 --> 00:14:50.070
There are a couple things that
are not exegesis.

00:14:50.070 --> 00:14:52.726
It's not exegesis to try to
figure out what actually

00:14:52.726 --> 00:14:53.299
happened.
 

00:14:53.299 --> 00:14:54.990
Did Jesus actually say this?
 

00:14:54.990 --> 00:14:57.100
Did Jesus actually believe that?
 

00:14:57.100 --> 00:14:59.851
That's part of the historical
Jesus quest which we'll talk

00:14:59.851 --> 00:15:02.940
about later in the semester too,
but exegesis doesn't do that.

00:15:02.940 --> 00:15:05.328
Exegesis doesn't assume you're
trying to read the text to get

00:15:05.328 --> 00:15:07.600
behind the text for something
that happened in history.

00:15:07.600 --> 00:15:11.080
Nor does exegesis try to figure
out is this true or not.

00:15:11.080 --> 00:15:14.220
We don't care if it's true or
not in an exegesis class.

00:15:14.220 --> 00:15:17.142
What we want to do is what did
the writer--what was the writer

00:15:17.142 --> 00:15:18.580
trying to do with this text?
 

00:15:18.580 --> 00:15:20.928
You have to imagine yourself in
an ancient context.

00:15:20.928 --> 00:15:24.283
What would he have been saying
to members of his own Christian

00:15:24.283 --> 00:15:26.100
community in the first century?
 

00:15:26.100 --> 00:15:29.618
This obviously means that we
read this text as not Jesus

00:15:29.618 --> 00:15:31.408
necessarily teaching this.
 

00:15:31.408 --> 00:15:33.360
We don't know yet whether Jesus
actually taught this.

00:15:33.360 --> 00:15:35.336
Matthew could have gotten it
from some written source,

00:15:35.336 --> 00:15:37.238
from some oral source,
or he could have just made it

00:15:37.238 --> 00:15:37.500
up.
 

00:15:37.500 --> 00:15:39.486
We'll talk about that problem
later when we talk about the

00:15:39.486 --> 00:15:40.149
historical Jesus.
 

00:15:40.149 --> 00:15:41.690
Right now we're not going to
concern ourselves,

00:15:41.690 --> 00:15:43.477
we're just going to say,
Matthew could have written this

00:15:43.477 --> 00:15:45.461
but we're trying to figure out
what did Matthew want to

00:15:45.461 --> 00:15:45.950
do with it.
 

00:15:45.950 --> 00:15:47.820
What was this testament to them?
 

00:15:47.820 --> 00:15:51.879
Obviously it means this writer
believes that the proper Gospel

00:15:51.879 --> 00:15:55.538
and the proper church should be
a Law abiding church.

00:15:55.538 --> 00:15:58.765
He's expecting people in his
church not to do away with the

00:15:58.765 --> 00:15:59.490
Jewish law.
 

00:15:59.490 --> 00:16:04.302
Look at "the
antitheses,"

00:16:04.302 --> 00:16:08.575
we call these,
the Matthean antithesis,

00:16:08.575 --> 00:16:12.849
5:21: "'You have heard
that it was said to those in

00:16:12.849 --> 00:16:15.879
ancient times you shall not
